SIMPLE: stead
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stead
<hw>Stead</hw> <pr>(st⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stede</ets> place, AS. <ets>stede</ets>; akin to LG. & D.
<ets>stede</ets>, OS. <ets>stad</ets>, <ets>stedi</ets>, OHG.
<ets>stat</ets>, G. <ets>statt</ets>, <ets>st⟦aum⟧tte</ets>, Icel.
<ets>sta⟦edh⟧r</ets>, Dan. <ets>sted</ets>, Sw. <ets>stad</ets>, Goth.
<ets>sta⟦thorn⟧s</ets>, and E. <ets>stand</ets>. ⟦root⟧163. See
<er>Stand</er>, and cf. <er>Staith</er>, <er>Stithy</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Place, or spot, in general.</def> <mark>[Obs., except
in composition.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fly, therefore, fly this fearful <qex>stead</qex> anon.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Place or room which another had, has, or might
have.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Stewards of your <xex>steads</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In <qex>stead</qex> of bounds, he a pillar set.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A frame on which a bed is laid; a bedstead.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The genial bed,⟦br⟧
Sallow the feet, the borders, and the <qex>stead</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A farmhouse and offices.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. &
Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The word is now commonly used as the last part of a
compound; as, farm<xex>stead</xex>, home<xex>stead</xex>,
road<xex>stead</xex>, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In stead of</b></col>, <cd>in place of. See
<er>Instead</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To stand in stead</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>To do stead</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to be of use or
great advantage.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The smallest act . . . shall <qex>stand</qex> us <qex>in</qex>
great <qex>stead</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here thy sword can <qex>do</qex> thee little <qex>stead</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stead</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stead
<hw>Stead</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To help; to support;
to benefit; to assist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Perhaps my succour or advisement meet,⟦br⟧
Mote <qex>stead</qex> you much your purpose to subdue.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It nothing <qex>steads</qex> us⟦br⟧
To chide him from our eaves.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fill the place of.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steadfast</ent>⟦br⟧
